Introduction - Business Problem¶

Bike sharing is an innovative mode of transportation that allows users to make trips using publicly available bikes. It consists of a fleet of specially designed, sturdy and durable bikes that are locked into a network of docking stations throughout the service area. The bikes can be unlocked from one station and return to any other station in the system, making bike share ideal for short, one-way trips. We will analyze the 2017 data for the Ford GoBike System (Now called BayWheels since its acquisition by Lyft.) We want to know what the most popular stations are so we can improve them and run promotions there. We also want to understand the behavior of our clientele so we can use these insights for future business planning.

Data¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area for the year 2017. It containts multiple features which we'll explore and analyze to answer some questions we will pose based on the data. You can download the .csv file containg the dataset used for this project directly from this link.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

Our cleaned dataset contains 519,700 and 10 main columns which are:

  1. duration_sec: Duration of each ride in seconds.

  2. start_time: Starting time information for the ride.

  3. end_time: Ending time information for the ride.

  4. start_station_id: ID of the start station.

  5. start_station_name: Name of the start station.

  6. end_station_id: ID of the end station.

  7. end_station_name: Name of the end station.

  8. bike_id: ID of the bike used in the ride.

  9. user_type: Type of user who made the ride (Subscriber or Customer).

  10. day_name: Name of the weekday (i.e. Sunday, Monday, etc.)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features we're interested in are duration_sec, start_time, and start_station_name.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

user_type and day_name will support our investigation a lot!

We can also make use of the end_station_name and end_time if we need to.

We will try to make all visualizations as explanatory as possible so we can use them directly in our report without having to polish them up again. This makes the EDA process much easier to follow while also conveying lots of explanations!

        color=color_dict[cluster],fill=True,fill_color=color_dict[cluster],

As we have more subscribers, does that mean that the average duration for subscriber rides is larger that the average duration for customer rides? We cannot possibly determine that without more analysis. Let's start with a boxplot to see the different data ranges.

In [46]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
sns.boxplot(x='user_type',y='duration_sec',data=df)
plt.title('Distribution of Ride Durations in Seconds per User Type',fontsize=20)
plt.ylabel('Duration (seconds)',fontsize=15)
plt.xlabel('User Type',fontsize=15);

We can see that the contorary to our initial hypothesis, the average ride duration for normal Customers is actually around 2 times bigger than the average ride duration for Subscribers!

This may indicate that subscribers usually take rides for predefined destinations, e.g. commuting to work. On the other hand, normal customers don't have a specific destination as all of them are casual riders and probably lots of them are tourists. If this were true, we should find the standard deviation for the customer user_type to be bigger than the standard deviation for the subscriber user_type

First, we'll use a bar plot to check the mean of both of them.

In [47]:
#First, check the mean per user_type
plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))

plt.ylabel('Duration (seconds)',fontsize=15)
plt.xlabel('User Type',fontsize=15);

And now to check the standard deviation, we'll use the estimator parameter.

In [48]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
sns.barplot(x='user_type',y='duration_sec',data=df,estimator=np.std)
plt.title('Standard Deviation for Ride Durations in Seconds per User Type',fontsize=20)
plt.ylabel('Standard Deviation for Duration (seconds)',fontsize=15)
plt.xlabel('User Type',fontsize=15);

And yes, the standard deviation for customer user_type is indeed higher than that of subscriber user_type.

Conclusion¶

Some Observations:¶

Our first finding illustrated how subscribers do in fact use the bikes for shorter rides no matter what station they originate from!

Interesting interactions between features:¶

We decided to check if this is because subscriber users probably use the bikes to commute, if they did, we expect to see bimodal distributions for them no matter the month of the year, or the day of the working week.

We found that to be true, and the only exception is on weekend where both user types are pretty similar in their usage.
